# Supabase Storage — Vector Buckets Reference

**Status**: Public Alpha (December 2025)

Vector Buckets are S3-backed vector storage with built-in similarity search.
They are NOT a replacement for pgvector — they serve a different purpose.

---

## pgvector vs Vector Buckets — Decision Guide

| Dimension | pgvector (Postgres) | Vector Buckets (Storage) |
|---|---|---|
| Scale | Up to ~1M vectors comfortably | Tens of millions of vectors |
| Storage cost | PostgreSQL storage pricing | S3 pricing (~10x cheaper at scale) |
| Query latency | 5–50ms (in-DB, no network hop) | 50–200ms (external storage) |
| JOIN with DB data | Native SQL JOIN | Not possible directly |
| Durability | PostgreSQL WAL, daily backups | S3 durability (99.999999999%) |
| Best for | User documents, chat history, core app data | Large archives, all product embeddings, public dataset |
| Index types | HNSW, IVFFlat | HNSW, Flat |
| API | SQL + supabase.rpc() | supabase.storage.vectors API |

### When to use pgvector
- You need to JOIN embeddings with your users/orders/posts tables
- Dataset is under ~500K vectors
- Low latency matters (under 20ms)
- Embeddings are tightly coupled to relational data

### When to use Vector Buckets
- Tens of millions of vectors (product catalogue, document archive)
- Cost is a concern at scale (S3 is 10x cheaper than Postgres storage)
- Batch ingestion of large corpora
- You don't need to JOIN with relational data

### Hybrid architecture (official Supabase recommendation)
```
pgvector: hot/recent embeddings — last 90 days, active users
          → fast JOIN with profiles/orders, low latency
Vector Buckets: archived embeddings — older data, full corpus
          → cost-efficient, bulk search across millions
```

